english:
  title: Yeongjeong Temple
  author: Seok Wolchan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Through the forest curves a spring from rocky hollows,
    Before the railing, the ancient tree casts emerald shade.
    When autumn arrives, the temple gate grows crisp and clear,
    As clouds return, the pine-crowned ridge deepens into mystery.

    Moss-worn stone tablets pass down the sacred traces of old,
    White walls hold new verses inscribed for the first time today.
    Long seated here, my spirit grows ever more serene,
    The temple bell's resonance sways the moon—the night grows still and deep.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem celebrates Yeongjeong Temple, likely a Buddhist monastery, blending natural landscape imagery with spiritual reflection.
  - key: ''
    value: The progression from external description (spring, forest, ancient tree) to internal transformation (spirit becoming serene) reflects the contemplative purpose of temple visits in Korean Buddhist tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The final image of the bell swaying the moon suggests the timeless, transcendent nature of spiritual practice—sound and celestial light merging in the profound stillness of night.
